  "verdict": "warn",
  "rationale": "Evidence shows that progressive bodyweight training (using challenging variations like lunges, Bulgarian split squats, and skater squats) can produce hypertrophy similar to barbell squats if sets are taken close to failure and intensity is high. However, simply sticking to light weight body squats (without progression or sufficient intensity) is unlikely to provide enough stimulus for optimal hypertrophy, especially for trained individuals. Barbell squats allow for reliable overload and may be more effective for reducing body fat percentage. If you choose bodyweight squats, ensure you progress the difficulty and train close to failure to maximize hypertrophy.",
  "citations": [1,2]
}

{
  "verdict": "warn",
  "rationale": "Evidence shows that progressive bodyweight training, when performed with sufficient intensity and volume, can produce similar hypertrophy gains as barbell squats in sedentary individuals, provided exercises are pushed close to failure. However, the studies used progressive bodyweight movements (lunges, split squats, skater squats) rather than only light bodyweight squats. Purely sticking to light weight body squats without progression or intensity may not elicit optimal hypertrophy, especially for trained individuals. Barbell squats may also be more effective for reducing body fat percentage.",
  "citations": [1,2]
}

